Your question appears to be an [XY Problem](http://meta.stackexchange.com/questions/66377/what-is-the-xy-problem) where you ask how to solve a specific code problem when the best solution is to use a completely different approach. 

Your question is &quot;why isn&#39;t `getHeight()` working like I want it to work&quot;, when the real issue is that you&#39;re using the wrong layout managers. You appear to want to create somewhat list of items held in a JScrollPane, that scrolls correctly and shows correctly, but the main JPanel that is held by the JScrollPane and that holds all the listing sub-components uses FlowLayout, a *very* limited layout manager, one that is useful mainly for very simple linear based layouts. For this situation, one possible solution is to have the main JPanel that is held by the scrollpane use a BoxLayout oriented to the page-axis. This way, components added will be added below previously added components. This way, using a BoxLayout, the JScrollPane will *automatically* size its viewport correctly, without you having to use any `getHeight()` kludges, a *brittle* kludge, as you are finding out.

For example, my [MRE](https://stackoverflow.com/help/minimal-reproducible-example) program:

